       <h3>Always-available solution engine</h3>
       <p>Every completed face, slice, and whole-cube turn is recorded in a reversible move ledger. SOLVE cancels unplayed queued work, safely lets a turn already in motion finish, inverts the completed move history, simplifies adjacent turns, and animates the exact return path to the solved state. Because every state in CUBED is produced by legal moves through this engine, the inverse sequence is an exact solver for any state the app can create.</p>
       <h3>Lighting and atmosphere</h3>
-      <p>A hemisphere light, key directional light, colored rim light, and low ambient light reveal the cube’s form. The key light uses PCF soft shadow mapping. A points-based starfield slowly rotates behind the scene, a shadow plane catches the cube’s soft silhouette, and the Synthwave theme fades in a large perspective grid.</p>
+      <p>A hemisphere light, key directional light, colored rim light, low ambient light, fog, a recolorable starfield, a shadow-catching floor, and an optional perspective grid create 25 distinct display environments. Each environment coordinates its layered CSS backdrop with the WebGL lighting so the cube feels placed in a deliberate space rather than merely recolored.</p>
       <h3>Smooth theme interpolation</h3>
-      <p>Theme changes update CSS custom properties for the glass interface and also interpolate every scene parameter over about one second: light colors, intensities, star opacity, grid opacity, and ground-shadow strength.</p>
+      <p>The Environment dropdown updates the layered background and glass-interface palette, then interpolates the WebGL scene over about one second: hemisphere, key, rim, ambient and fog colors, light intensities, star color/size/speed/opacity, grid colors/opacity, and ground-shadow color/strength.</p>
       <h3>No-framework interface</h3>
       <p>The entire interface is ordinary HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. CSS custom properties drive accents, <code>backdrop-filter</code> creates glass surfaces, Flexbox and Grid build the controls, and media queries transform the guide into a mobile bottom sheet. Chakra Petch and Sora are delivered by Google Fonts with system fallbacks.</p>
       <h3>Input and hosting</h3>
@@ -1019,8 +1003,12 @@
       <p><strong>GUIDE</strong> opens the lesson panel. The header shows <strong>STEP n / 8</strong> and eight progress ticks. Back and Next navigate the lessons; the step-eight button reads <strong>Start over</strong> and returns to step one. Every algorithm block has a <strong>▶ Play</strong> button that queues the displayed moves on the cube from its current state. Guide Play is temporarily ignored during AUTO SOLVE.</p>
       <p>The guide teaches: meeting the cube and notation, the white cross, white corners, middle-layer edges, the yellow cross, lining up yellow edges, placing yellow corners, and twisting the final corners. Closing and reopening GUIDE preserves the current lesson while the page remains open.</p>
 
-      <h3>Visual themes</h3>
-      <p>The top pills select <strong>Nebula</strong>, <strong>Synthwave</strong>, <strong>Daylight</strong>, or <strong>Ember</strong>. Each changes the background, interface accent, glass panels, scene lighting, rim light, star visibility, ground shadow, and—on Synthwave—the perspective grid. Daylight switches to light glass and dark text. Scene lighting blends smoothly instead of jumping.</p>
+      <h3>Theme Environment dropdown</h3>
+      <p>The header’s <strong>Environment</strong> dropdown contains 25 coordinated display spaces. Each selection changes the layered page backdrop, accent color, glass panels, text contrast, WebGL hemisphere/key/rim/ambient lighting, fog, star color and motion, ground shadow, and—where appropriate—the perspective grid. Light environments automatically use light glass with dark text. Scene parameters blend smoothly rather than jumping.</p>
